   "source": [
    "# Function 3: Extract Raster Subset ‚úÇÔ∏è\n",
    "\n",
    "**Welcome to spatial subsetting!**\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, you'll learn how to build the `extract_raster_subset()` function step by step. This is like using the \"Clip Raster by Extent\" tool in QGIS - but with full programmatic control and memory efficiency.\n",
    "\n",
    "## üéØ What This Function Does\n",
    "- Defines a spatial window using geographic coordinates (bounding box)\n",
    "- Converts geographic bounds to pixel coordinates efficiently\n",
    "- Uses windowed reading to extract only the needed portion (saves memory!)\n",
    "- Preserves original CRS and metadata in the subset\n",
    "- Calculates new spatial transform for the subset\n",
    "- Optionally saves the subset to a new file\n",
    "- Returns the subset array and updated metadata\n",
    "\n",
    "## üîß Function Signature\n",
    "```python\n",
    "def extract_raster_subset(raster_path, window_bounds, output_path=None):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        raster_path (str): Path to input raster file\n",
    "        window_bounds (tuple): Geographic bounds (left, bottom, right, top)\n",
    "        output_path (str, optional): Path to save subset (if desired)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        dict: Dictionary with subset array, metadata, and window info\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## üöÄ Step 1: Import Required Libraries\n",
    "\n",
    "We need rasterio's windowing tools and coordinate transformation functions:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import rasterio\n",
    "from rasterio.windows import Window, from_bounds\n",
    "from rasterio.transform import from_bounds as transform_from_bounds\n",
    "from rasterio.enums import Resampling\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from pathlib import Path\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib.patches as patches\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"‚úÖ Rasterio version: {rasterio.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(f\"‚úÖ NumPy version: {np.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(\"‚úÇÔ∏è Ready for spatial subsetting!\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## üìÅ Step 2: Load and Examine Our Sample Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's start with our elevation data and understand its full extent:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Set up our data path\n",
